article.headline: Washington shoots season-high 51 percent
article.linkText: Wizards snap skid while prolonging Sonics'
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- There was no avoiding it. Someone's losing streak had to end. At least one coach would go home not complaining about effort, discipline or heart. That small reward went to the Washington Wizards, who stopped a three-game slide and extended the Seattle SuperSonics' skid to four with a 99-84 victory Saturday night. "We played a team that was a little bit down because of their travel and their schedule," Washington coach Eddie Jordan said. "We redeemed ourselves after the game last night." Both teams were tired from playing -- and losing badly -- the night before, and had their effort questioned by their respective coaches in the previous 24 hours. Accordingly, the game was hardly an NBA clinic, with 41 combined turnovers and barely enough action to get the crowd involved for much of the game. Seattle's defense was lax enough for Washington to shoot a season-high 51 percent. Larry Hughes scored 27 points to lead the Wizards, who won for only the third time in 15 games. Rookie Jarvis Hayes, back in the starting lineup after the latest shuffle by Jordan, scored 14 points and had a career-high 13 rebounds. "It wasn't pretty, but it was aggressive," Hughes said. Ray Allen scored 19 points to lead the Sonics, who lost by 20 at New York on Friday and are 0-2 on a four-game East Coast road trip. They missed many open outside jumpers and shot 39 percent -- their third straight game at below 40 percent. All four losses in the losing streak have come against teams with losing records. "Right now I'm not reaching them," coach Nate McMillan said. "We're playing poor. We're not playing together. We're not stopping anyone defensively. New York, that's a pretty good team. Washington is a team that's struggling, similar to us. I feel we should win this game, and we didn't perform again." The Sonics made just 8 of 30 3-pointers. They clearly didn't have their legs, having arrived in Washington at 3:30 a.m. following plane problems delaying the team's departure from New York. "We had side effects from it, but we still have to play the games," said Allen, who was 6-for-20 from the field. The difference was the third quarter, when Seattle made 6 of 24 shots. The usually reliable Brent Barry missed a pair of open jumpers, and Vladimir Radmanovic and Ronald Murray shot airballs on the same possession. The Wizards had success playing a small lineup, and Hayes' dunk after a steal highlighted an 8-0 run early in the third. Kwame Brown asserted himself with a dunk and a pair of free throws, and Hughes hit a 3-pointer to get the lead to 14. Hughes embarrassingly had the ball slip from his hands on a breakaway dunk late in the period, but the Wizards took a 12-point lead into the fourth quarter. The Sonics didn't get closer than eight in the final period.

Game notes
Sonics forward Reggie Evans missed the game with the flu. ... The Wizards beat Seattle at home for the first time since the day the MCI Center opened -- Dec. 2, 1997. ... The Wizards began a stretch in which they play nine of 10 games at home. ... With Hayes starting for Brendan Haywood, the Wizards started their 11th different lineup this season. ... The four-game losing streak matches Seattle's season high.
